Organised labour in oil and gas industry under the aegis of Nigeria Union of Petroleum and Natural Gas Workers (NUPENG) and Petroleum and Natural Gas Senior Staff Association of Nigeria (PENGASSAN) yesterday fulfilled their pledge to paralyse business activities of General Electric (GE) over anti-labour activities. The two unions led by PENGASSAN zonal chairman, Comrade Onovae Simon in exclusive interviews at the scene in Victoria Island, Lagos,  blamed the management of General Electric for reneging from the promised it made with Labour and Employment Minister, Senator Chris Ngige to pay the aggrieved workers their entitlements, five years after sacking of over 400 workers without following due process. According to Simon, who led the PENGASSAN workers in the picketing, the union vowed that the picketing will only end when the GE management pay the workers. He said: “GE has no respect to our law in Nigeria. Something they will not try in USA, their home country, they are trying to do it here in Nigeria. We will not allow that from them. Since the management is disrespecting the federal government by not honouring our Labour Minister and the SSS that intervened in order to create industrial peace, so we too will picket them until they yield to our demand. Our affected members are suffering as they are waiting for their entitlements.” Likewise, Comrade Tayo Aboyegi, the zonal chairman, who led  the NUPENG arm in the picketing, said they will picket the firm for 41days since they have no regards to our minister and SSS. He said they pledged to pay the members of the union their entitlements since 2016. The picketing started at 6.30am on Monday. The workers, who closed the main gate of the firm, while singing solidarity songs, said their action  against the company was prompted by the refusal of Arco Group, an employment contractor to General Electric to pay their severance packages that is long overdue.